  15 """This API defines FeatureColumn abstraction.
  16 
  17 FeatureColumns provide a high level abstraction for ingesting and representing
  18 features. FeatureColumns are also the primary way of encoding features for
  19 canned `tf.estimator.Estimator`s.
  20 
  21 When using FeatureColumns with `Estimators`, the type of feature column you
  22 should choose depends on (1) the feature type and (2) the model type.
  23 
  24 1. Feature type:
  25 
  26   * Continuous features can be represented by `numeric_column`.
  27   * Categorical features can be represented by any `categorical_column_with_*`
  28   column:
  29     - `categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list`
  30     - `categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file`
  31     - `categorical_column_with_hash_bucket`
  32     - `categorical_column_with_identity`
  33     - `weighted_categorical_column`
  34 
  35 2. Model type:
  36 
  37   * Deep neural network models (`DNNClassifier`, `DNNRegressor`).
  38 
  39     Continuous features can be directly fed into deep neural network models.
  40 
  41       age_column = numeric_column("age")
  42 
  43     To feed sparse features into DNN models, wrap the column with
  44     `embedding_column` or `indicator_column`. `indicator_column` is recommended
  45     for features with only a few possible values. For features with many
  46     possible values, to reduce the size of your model, `embedding_column` is
  47     recommended.
  48 
  49       embedded_dept_column = embedding_column(
  50           categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list(
  51               "department", ["math", "philosophy", ...]), dimension=10)
  52 
  53   * Wide (aka linear) models (`LinearClassifier`, `LinearRegressor`).
  54 
  55     Sparse features can be fed directly into linear models. They behave like an
  56     indicator column but with an efficient implementation.
  57 
  58       dept_column = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list("department",
  59           ["math", "philosophy", "english"])
  60 
  61     It is recommended that continuous features be bucketized before being
  62     fed into linear models.
  63 
  64       bucketized_age_column = bucketized_column(
  65           source_column=age_column,
  66           boundaries=[18, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55, 60, 65])
  67 
  68     Sparse features can be crossed (also known as conjuncted or combined) in
  69     order to form non-linearities, and then fed into linear models.
  70 
  71       cross_dept_age_column = crossed_column(
  72           columns=["department", bucketized_age_column],
  73           hash_bucket_size=1000)
  74 
  75 Example of building canned `Estimator`s using FeatureColumns:
  76 
  77   ```python
  78   # Define features and transformations
  79   deep_feature_columns = [age_column, embedded_dept_column]
  80   wide_feature_columns = [dept_column, bucketized_age_column,
  81       cross_dept_age_column]
  82 
  83   # Build deep model
  84   estimator = DNNClassifier(
  85       feature_columns=deep_feature_columns,
  86       hidden_units=[500, 250, 50])
  87   estimator.train(...)
  88 
  89   # Or build a wide model
  90   estimator = LinearClassifier(
  91       feature_columns=wide_feature_columns)
  92   estimator.train(...)
  93 
  94   # Or build a wide and deep model!
  95   estimator = DNNLinearCombinedClassifier(
  96       linear_feature_columns=wide_feature_columns,
  97       dnn_feature_columns=deep_feature_columns,
  98       dnn_hidden_units=[500, 250, 50])
  99   estimator.train(...)
 100   ```
 101 
 102 
 103 FeatureColumns can also be transformed into a generic input layer for
 104 custom models using `input_layer`.
 105 
 106 Example of building model using FeatureColumns, this can be used in a
 107 `model_fn` which is given to the {tf.estimator.Estimator}:
 108 
 109   ```python
 110   # Building model via layers
 111 
 112   deep_feature_columns = [age_column, embedded_dept_column]
 113   columns_to_tensor = parse_feature_columns_from_examples(
 114       serialized=my_data,
 115       feature_columns=deep_feature_columns)
 116   first_layer = input_layer(
 117       features=columns_to_tensor,
 118       feature_columns=deep_feature_columns)
 119   second_layer = fully_connected(first_layer, ...)
 120   ```
 121 
 122 NOTE: Functions prefixed with "_" indicate experimental or private parts of
 123 the API subject to change, and should not be relied upon!
 124 """

 167 def _internal_input_layer(features,
 168                           feature_columns,
 169                           weight_collections=None,
 170                           trainable=True,
 171                           cols_to_vars=None,
 172                           scope=None,
 173                           cols_to_output_tensors=None,
 174                           from_template=False):
 175   """See input_layer. `scope` is a name or variable scope to use."""
 176 
 177   feature_columns = _normalize_feature_columns(feature_columns)
 178   for column in feature_columns:
 179     if not isinstance(column, _DenseColumn):
 180       raise ValueError(
 181           'Items of feature_columns must be a _DenseColumn. '
 182           'You can wrap a categorical column with an '
 183           'embedding_column or indicator_column. Given: {}'.format(column))
 184   weight_collections = list(weight_collections or [])
 185   if ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES not in weight_collections:
 186     weight_collections.append(ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES)
 187   if ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES not in weight_collections:
 188     weight_collections.append(ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES)
 189 
 190   def _get_logits():  # pylint: disable=missing-docstring
 191     builder = _LazyBuilder(features)
 192     output_tensors = []
 193     ordered_columns = []
 194     for column in sorted(feature_columns, key=lambda x: x.name):
 195       ordered_columns.append(column)
 196       with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 197           None, default_name=column._var_scope_name):  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 198         tensor = column._get_dense_tensor(  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 199             builder,
 200             weight_collections=weight_collections,
 201             trainable=trainable)
 202         num_elements = column._variable_shape.num_elements()  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 203         batch_size = array_ops.shape(tensor)[0]
 204         output_tensor = array_ops.reshape(
 205             tensor, shape=(batch_size, num_elements))
 206         output_tensors.append(output_tensor)
 207         if cols_to_vars is not None:
 208           # Retrieve any variables created (some _DenseColumn's don't create
 209           # variables, in which case an empty list is returned).
 210           cols_to_vars[column] = ops.get_collection(
 211               ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES,
 212               scope=variable_scope.get_variable_scope().name)
 213         if cols_to_output_tensors is not None:
 214           cols_to_output_tensors[column] = output_tensor
 215     _verify_static_batch_size_equality(output_tensors, ordered_columns)
 216     return array_ops.concat(output_tensors, 1)
 217 
 218   # If we're constructing from the `make_template`, that by default adds a
 219   # variable scope with the name of the layer. In that case, we dont want to
 220   # add another `variable_scope` as that would break checkpoints.
 221   if from_template:
 222     return _get_logits()
 223   else:
 224     with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 225         scope, default_name='input_layer', values=features.values()):
 226       return _get_logits()

 229 @tf_export('feature_column.input_layer')
 230 def input_layer(features,
 231                 feature_columns,
 232                 weight_collections=None,
 233                 trainable=True,
 234                 cols_to_vars=None,
 235                 cols_to_output_tensors=None):
 236   """Returns a dense `Tensor` as input layer based on given `feature_columns`.
 237 
 238   Generally a single example in training data is described with FeatureColumns.
 239   At the first layer of the model, this column oriented data should be converted
 240   to a single `Tensor`.
 241 
 242   Example:
 243 
 244   ```python
 245   price = numeric_column('price')
 246   keywords_embedded = embedding_column(
 247       categorical_column_with_hash_bucket("keywords", 10K), dimensions=16)
 248   columns = [price, keywords_embedded, ...]
 249   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
 250   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
 251   for units in [128, 64, 32]:
 252     dense_tensor = tf.layers.dense(dense_tensor, units, tf.nn.relu)
 253   prediction = tf.layers.dense(dense_tensor, 1)
 254   ```
 255 
 256   Args:
 257     features: A mapping from key to tensors. `_FeatureColumn`s look up via these
 258       keys. For example `numeric_column('price')` will look at 'price' key in
 259       this dict. Values can be a `SparseTensor` or a `Tensor` depends on
 260       corresponding `_FeatureColumn`.
 261     feature_columns: An iterable containing the FeatureColumns to use as inputs
 262       to your model. All items should be instances of classes derived from
 263       `_DenseColumn` such as `numeric_column`, `embedding_column`,
 264       `bucketized_column`, `indicator_column`. If you have categorical features,
 265       you can wrap them with an `embedding_column` or `indicator_column`.
 266     weight_collections: A list of collection names to which the Variable will be
 267       added. Note that variables will also be added to collections
 268       `tf.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES` and `ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES`.
 269     trainable: If `True` also add the variable to the graph collection
 270       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.Variable`).
 271     cols_to_vars: If not `None`, must be a dictionary that will be filled with a
 272       mapping from `_FeatureColumn` to list of `Variable`s.  For example, after
 273       the call, we might have cols_to_vars =
 274       {_EmbeddingColumn(
 275         categorical_column=_HashedCategoricalColumn(
 276           key='sparse_feature', hash_bucket_size=5, dtype=tf.string),
 277         dimension=10): [<tf.Variable 'some_variable:0' shape=(5, 10),
 278                         <tf.Variable 'some_variable:1' shape=(5, 10)]}
 279       If a column creates no variables, its value will be an empty list.
 280     cols_to_output_tensors: If not `None`, must be a dictionary that will be
 281       filled with a mapping from '_FeatureColumn' to the associated
 282       output `Tensor`s.
 283 
 284   Returns:
 285     A `Tensor` which represents input layer of a model. Its shape
 286     is (batch_size, first_layer_dimension) and its dtype is `float32`.
 287     first_layer_dimension is determined based on given `feature_columns`.
 288 
 289   Raises:
 290     ValueError: if an item in `feature_columns` is not a `_DenseColumn`.
 291   """
 292   return _internal_input_layer(
 293       features,
 294       feature_columns,
 295       weight_collections=weight_collections,
 296       trainable=trainable,
 297       cols_to_vars=cols_to_vars,
 298       cols_to_output_tensors=cols_to_output_tensors)
 299

 301 # TODO(akshayka): InputLayer should be a subclass of Layer, and it
 302 # should implement the logic in input_layer using Layer's build-and-call
 303 # paradigm; input_layer should create an instance of InputLayer and
 304 # return the result of invoking its apply method, just as functional layers do.
 305 class InputLayer(object):
 306   """An object-oriented version of `input_layer` that reuses variables."""
 307 
 308   def __init__(self,
 309                feature_columns,
 310                weight_collections=None,
 311                trainable=True,
 312                cols_to_vars=None,
 313                name='feature_column_input_layer',
 314                create_scope_now=True):
 315     """See `input_layer`."""
 316 
 317     self._feature_columns = feature_columns
 318     self._weight_collections = weight_collections
 319     self._trainable = trainable
 320     self._cols_to_vars = cols_to_vars
 321     self._name = name
 322     self._input_layer_template = template.make_template(
 323         self._name, _internal_input_layer, create_scope_now_=create_scope_now)
 324     self._scope = self._input_layer_template.variable_scope
 325 
 326   def __call__(self, features):
 327     return self._input_layer_template(
 328         features=features,
 329         feature_columns=self._feature_columns,
 330         weight_collections=self._weight_collections,
 331         trainable=self._trainable,
 332         cols_to_vars=None,
 333         from_template=True)
 334 
 335   @property
 336   def name(self):
 337     return self._name
 338 
 339   @property
 340   def non_trainable_variables(self):
 341     return self._input_layer_template.non_trainable_variables
 342 
 343   @property
 344   def non_trainable_weights(self):
 345     return self._input_layer_template.non_trainable_weights
 346 
 347   @property
 348   def trainable_variables(self):
 349     return self._input_layer_template.trainable_variables
 350 
 351   @property
 352   def trainable_weights(self):
 353     return self._input_layer_template.trainable_weights
 354 
 355   @property
 356   def variables(self):
 357     return self._input_layer_template.variables
 358 
 359   @property
 360   def weights(self):
 361     return self._input_layer_template.weights

 364 @tf_export('feature_column.linear_model')
 365 def linear_model(features,
 366                  feature_columns,
 367                  units=1,
 368                  sparse_combiner='sum',
 369                  weight_collections=None,
 370                  trainable=True,
 371                  cols_to_vars=None):
 372   """Returns a linear prediction `Tensor` based on given `feature_columns`.
 373 
 374   This function generates a weighted sum based on output dimension `units`.
 375   Weighted sum refers to logits in classification problems. It refers to the
 376   prediction itself for linear regression problems.
 377 
 378   Note on supported columns: `linear_model` treats categorical columns as
 379   `indicator_column`s. To be specific, assume the input as `SparseTensor` looks
 380   like:
 381 
 382   ```python
 383     shape = [2, 2]
 384     {
 385         [0, 0]: "a"
 386         [1, 0]: "b"
 387         [1, 1]: "c"
 388     }
 389   ```
 390   `linear_model` assigns weights for the presence of "a", "b", "c' implicitly,
 391   just like `indicator_column`, while `input_layer` explicitly requires wrapping
 392   each of categorical columns with an `embedding_column` or an
 393   `indicator_column`.
 394 
 395   Example of usage:
 396 
 397   ```python
 398   price = numeric_column('price')
 399   price_buckets = bucketized_column(price, boundaries=[0., 10., 100., 1000.])
 400   keywords = categorical_column_with_hash_bucket("keywords", 10K)
 401   keywords_price = crossed_column('keywords', price_buckets, ...)
 402   columns = [price_buckets, keywords, keywords_price ...]
 403   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
 404   prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
 405   ```
 406 
 407   Args:
 408     features: A mapping from key to tensors. `_FeatureColumn`s look up via these
 409       keys. For example `numeric_column('price')` will look at 'price' key in
 410       this dict. Values are `Tensor` or `SparseTensor` depending on
 411       corresponding `_FeatureColumn`.
 412     feature_columns: An iterable containing the FeatureColumns to use as inputs
 413       to your model. All items should be instances of classes derived from
 414       `_FeatureColumn`s.
 415     units: An integer, dimensionality of the output space. Default value is 1.
 416     sparse_combiner: A string specifying how to reduce if a categorical column
 417       is multivalent. Except `numeric_column`, almost all columns passed to
 418       `linear_model` are considered as categorical columns.  It combines each
 419       categorical column independently. Currently "mean", "sqrtn" and "sum" are
 420       supported, with "sum" the default for linear model. "sqrtn" often achieves
 421       good accuracy, in particular with bag-of-words columns.
 422         * "sum": do not normalize features in the column
 423         * "mean": do l1 normalization on features in the column
 424         * "sqrtn": do l2 normalization on features in the column
 425       For example, for two features represented as the categorical columns:
 426 
 427       ```python
 428         # Feature 1
 429 
 430         shape = [2, 2]
 431         {
 432             [0, 0]: "a"
 433             [0, 1]: "b"
 434             [1, 0]: "c"
 435         }
 436 
 437         # Feature 2
 438 
 439         shape = [2, 3]
 440         {
 441             [0, 0]: "d"
 442             [1, 0]: "e"
 443             [1, 1]: "f"
 444             [1, 2]: "g"
 445         }
 446       ```
 447       with `sparse_combiner` as "mean", the linear model outputs conceptly are:
 448       ```
 449         y_0 = 1.0 / 2.0 * ( w_a + w_ b) + w_c + b_0
 450         y_1 = w_d + 1.0 / 3.0 * ( w_e + w_ f + w_g) + b_1
 451       ```
 452       where `y_i` is the output, `b_i` is the bias, and `w_x` is the weight
 453       assigned to the presence of `x` in the input features.
 454     weight_collections: A list of collection names to which the Variable will be
 455       added. Note that, variables will also be added to collections
 456       `tf.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES` and `ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES`.
 457     trainable: If `True` also add the variable to the graph collection
 458       `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.Variable`).
 459     cols_to_vars: If not `None`, must be a dictionary that will be filled with a
 460       mapping from `_FeatureColumn` to associated list of `Variable`s.  For
 461       example, after the call, we might have cols_to_vars = {
 462         _NumericColumn(
 463           key='numeric_feature1', shape=(1,):
 464         [<tf.Variable 'linear_model/price2/weights:0' shape=(1, 1)>],
 465         'bias': [<tf.Variable 'linear_model/bias_weights:0' shape=(1,)>],
 466         _NumericColumn(
 467           key='numeric_feature2', shape=(2,)):
 468         [<tf.Variable 'linear_model/price1/weights:0' shape=(2, 1)>]}
 469       If a column creates no variables, its value will be an empty list. Note
 470       that cols_to_vars will also contain a string key 'bias' that maps to a
 471       list of Variables.
 472 
 473   Returns:
 474     A `Tensor` which represents predictions/logits of a linear model. Its shape
 475     is (batch_size, units) and its dtype is `float32`.
 476 
 477   Raises:
 478     ValueError: if an item in `feature_columns` is neither a `_DenseColumn`
 479       nor `_CategoricalColumn`.
 480   """
 481   with variable_scope.variable_scope(None, 'linear_model') as vs:
 482     model_name = _strip_leading_slashes(vs.name)
 483   linear_model_layer = _LinearModel(
 484       feature_columns=feature_columns,
 485       units=units,
 486       sparse_combiner=sparse_combiner,
 487       weight_collections=weight_collections,
 488       trainable=trainable,
 489       name=model_name)
 490   retval = linear_model_layer(features)  # pylint: disable=not-callable
 491   if cols_to_vars is not None:
 492     cols_to_vars.update(linear_model_layer.cols_to_vars())
 493   return retval

 496 def _add_to_collections(var, weight_collections):
 497   """Adds a var to the list of weight_collections provided.
 498 
 499   Handles the case for partitioned and non-partitioned variables.
 500 
 501   Args:
 502     var: A variable or Partitioned Variable.
 503     weight_collections: List of collections to add variable to.
 504   """
 505   for weight_collection in weight_collections:
 506     # The layer self.add_variable call already adds it to GLOBAL_VARIABLES.
 507     if weight_collection == ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES:
 508       continue
 509     # TODO(rohanj): Explore adding a _get_variable_list method on `Variable`
 510     # so that we don't have to do this check.
 511     if isinstance(var, variables.PartitionedVariable):
 512       for constituent_var in list(var):
 513         ops.add_to_collection(weight_collection, constituent_var)
 514     else:
 515       ops.add_to_collection(weight_collection, var)
 516

 518 class _FCLinearWrapper(base.Layer):
 519   """Wraps a _FeatureColumn in a layer for use in a linear model.
 520 
 521   See `linear_model` above.
 522   """
 523 
 524   def __init__(self,
 525                feature_column,
 526                units=1,
 527                sparse_combiner='sum',
 528                weight_collections=None,
 529                trainable=True,
 530                name=None,
 531                **kwargs):
 532     super(_FCLinearWrapper, self).__init__(
 533         trainable=trainable, name=name, **kwargs)
 534     self._feature_column = feature_column
 535     self._units = units
 536     self._sparse_combiner = sparse_combiner
 537     self._weight_collections = weight_collections
 538 
 539   def build(self, _):
 540     if isinstance(self._feature_column, _CategoricalColumn):
 541       weight = self.add_variable(
 542           name='weights',
 543           shape=(self._feature_column._num_buckets, self._units),  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 544           initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
 545           trainable=self.trainable)
 546     else:
 547       num_elements = self._feature_column._variable_shape.num_elements()  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 548       weight = self.add_variable(
 549           name='weights',
 550           shape=[num_elements, self._units],
 551           initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
 552           trainable=self.trainable)
 553     _add_to_collections(weight, self._weight_collections)
 554     self._weight_var = weight
 555     self.built = True
 556 
 557   def call(self, builder):
 558     weighted_sum = _create_weighted_sum(
 559         column=self._feature_column,
 560         builder=builder,
 561         units=self._units,
 562         sparse_combiner=self._sparse_combiner,
 563         weight_collections=self._weight_collections,
 564         trainable=self.trainable,
 565         weight_var=self._weight_var)
 566     return weighted_sum
 567

 569 class _BiasLayer(base.Layer):
 570   """A layer for the bias term.
 571   """
 572 
 573   def __init__(self,
 574                units=1,
 575                trainable=True,
 576                weight_collections=None,
 577                name=None,
 578                **kwargs):
 579     super(_BiasLayer, self).__init__(trainable=trainable, name=name, **kwargs)
 580     self._units = units
 581     self._weight_collections = weight_collections
 582 
 583   def build(self, _):
 584     self._bias_variable = self.add_variable(
 585         'bias_weights',
 586         shape=[self._units],
 587         initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
 588         trainable=self.trainable)
 589     _add_to_collections(self._bias_variable, self._weight_collections)
 590     self.built = True
 591 
 592   def call(self, _):
 593     return self._bias_variable

 596 def _get_expanded_variable_list(variable):
 597   if (isinstance(variable, variables.Variable) or
 598       resource_variable_ops.is_resource_variable(variable)):
 599     return [variable]  # Single variable case.
 600   else:  # Must be a PartitionedVariable, so convert into a list.
 601     return list(variable)

 605   return name.rsplit('/', 1)[-1]

 607 
 608 class _LinearModel(training.Model):
 609   """Creates a linear model using feature columns.
 610 
 611   See `linear_model` for details.
 612   """
 613 
 614   def __init__(self,
 615                feature_columns,
 616                units=1,
 617                sparse_combiner='sum',
 618                weight_collections=None,
 619                trainable=True,
 620                name=None,
 621                **kwargs):
 622     super(_LinearModel, self).__init__(name=name, **kwargs)
 623     self._feature_columns = _normalize_feature_columns(
 624         feature_columns)
 625     self._weight_collections = list(weight_collections or [])
 626     if ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES not in self._weight_collections:
 627       self._weight_collections.append(ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES)
 628     if ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES not in self._weight_collections:
 629       self._weight_collections.append(ops.GraphKeys.MODEL_VARIABLES)
 630 
 631     column_layers = {}
 632     for column in sorted(self._feature_columns, key=lambda x: x.name):
 633       with variable_scope.variable_scope(
 634           None, default_name=column._var_scope_name) as vs:  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 635         # Having the fully expressed variable scope name ends up doubly
 636         # expressing the outer scope (scope with which this method was called)
 637         # in the name of the variable that would get created.
 638         column_name = _strip_leading_slashes(vs.name)
 639       column_layer = _FCLinearWrapper(column, units, sparse_combiner,
 640                                       self._weight_collections, trainable,
 641                                       column_name, **kwargs)
 642       column_layers[column_name] = column_layer
 643     self._column_layers = self._add_layers(column_layers)
 644     self._bias_layer = _BiasLayer(
 645         units=units,
 646         trainable=trainable,
 647         weight_collections=self._weight_collections,
 648         name='bias_layer',
 649         **kwargs)
 650     self._cols_to_vars = {}
 651 
 652   def cols_to_vars(self):
 653     """Returns a dict mapping _FeatureColumns to variables.
 654 
 655     See `linear_model` for more information.
 656     This is not populated till `call` is called i.e. layer is built.
 657     """
 658     return self._cols_to_vars
 659 
 660   def call(self, features):
 661     with variable_scope.variable_scope(self.name):
 662       for column in self._feature_columns:
 663         if not isinstance(column, (_DenseColumn, _CategoricalColumn)):
 664           raise ValueError(
 665               'Items of feature_columns must be either a '
 666               '_DenseColumn or _CategoricalColumn. Given: {}'.format(column))
 667       weighted_sums = []
 668       ordered_columns = []
 669       builder = _LazyBuilder(features)
 670       for layer in sorted(self._column_layers.values(), key=lambda x: x.name):
 671         column = layer._feature_column  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 672         ordered_columns.append(column)
 673         weighted_sum = layer(builder)
 674         weighted_sums.append(weighted_sum)
 675         self._cols_to_vars[column] = ops.get_collection(
 676             ops.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES, scope=layer.scope_name)
 677 
 678       _verify_static_batch_size_equality(weighted_sums, ordered_columns)
 679       predictions_no_bias = math_ops.add_n(
 680           weighted_sums, name='weighted_sum_no_bias')
 681       predictions = nn_ops.bias_add(
 682           predictions_no_bias,
 683           self._bias_layer(  # pylint: disable=not-callable
 684               builder,
 685               scope=variable_scope.get_variable_scope()),  # pylint: disable=not-callable
 686           name='weighted_sum')
 687       bias = self._bias_layer.variables[0]
 688       self._cols_to_vars['bias'] = _get_expanded_variable_list(bias)
 689     return predictions
 690 
 691   def _add_layers(self, layers):
 692     # "Magic" required for keras.Model classes to track all the variables in
 693     # a list of layers.Layer objects.
 694     # TODO(ashankar): Figure out API so user code doesn't have to do this.
 695     for name, layer in layers.items():
 696       setattr(self, 'layer-%s' % name, layer)
 697     return layers
 698

 700 def _transform_features(features, feature_columns):
 701   """Returns transformed features based on features columns passed in.
 702 
 703   Please note that most probably you would not need to use this function. Please
 704   check `input_layer` and `linear_model` to see whether they will
 705   satisfy your use case or not.
 706 
 707   Example:
 708 
 709   ```python
 710   # Define features and transformations
 711   crosses_a_x_b = crossed_column(
 712       columns=["sparse_feature_a", "sparse_feature_b"], hash_bucket_size=10000)
 713   price_buckets = bucketized_column(
 714       source_column=numeric_column("price"), boundaries=[...])
 715 
 716   columns = [crosses_a_x_b, price_buckets]
 717   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
 718   transformed = transform_features(features=features, feature_columns=columns)
 719 
 720   assertCountEqual(columns, transformed.keys())
 721   ```
 722 
 723   Args:
 724     features: A mapping from key to tensors. `_FeatureColumn`s look up via these
 725       keys. For example `numeric_column('price')` will look at 'price' key in
 726       this dict. Values can be a `SparseTensor` or a `Tensor` depends on
 727       corresponding `_FeatureColumn`.
 728     feature_columns: An iterable containing all the `_FeatureColumn`s.
 729 
 730   Returns:
 731     A `dict` mapping `_FeatureColumn` to `Tensor` and `SparseTensor` values.
 732   """
 733   feature_columns = _normalize_feature_columns(feature_columns)
 734   outputs = {}
 735   with ops.name_scope(
 736       None, default_name='transform_features', values=features.values()):
 737     builder = _LazyBuilder(features)
 738     for column in sorted(feature_columns, key=lambda x: x.name):
 739       with ops.name_scope(None, default_name=column.name):
 740         outputs[column] = builder.get(column)
 741   return outputs
 742 
 743 
 744 @tf_export('feature_column.make_parse_example_spec')
 745 def make_parse_example_spec(feature_columns):
 746   """Creates parsing spec dictionary from input feature_columns.
 747 
 748   The returned dictionary can be used as arg 'features' in `tf.parse_example`.
 749 
 750   Typical usage example:
 751 
 752   ```python
 753   # Define features and transformations
 754   feature_a = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(...)
 755   feature_b = numeric_column(...)
 756   feature_c_bucketized = bucketized_column(numeric_column("feature_c"), ...)
 757   feature_a_x_feature_c = crossed_column(
 758       columns=["feature_a", feature_c_bucketized], ...)
 759 
 760   feature_columns = set(
 761       [feature_b, feature_c_bucketized, feature_a_x_feature_c])
 762   features = tf.parse_example(
 763       serialized=serialized_examples,
 764       features=make_parse_example_spec(feature_columns))
 765   ```
 766 
 767   For the above example, make_parse_example_spec would return the dict:
 768 
 769   ```python
 770   {
 771       "feature_a": parsing_ops.VarLenFeature(tf.string),
 772       "feature_b": parsing_ops.FixedLenFeature([1], dtype=tf.float32),
 773       "feature_c": parsing_ops.FixedLenFeature([1], dtype=tf.float32)
 774   }
 775   ```
 776 
 777   Args:
 778     feature_columns: An iterable containing all feature columns. All items
 779       should be instances of classes derived from `_FeatureColumn`.
 780 
 781   Returns:
 782     A dict mapping each feature key to a `FixedLenFeature` or `VarLenFeature`
 783     value.
 784 
 785   Raises:
 786     ValueError: If any of the given `feature_columns` is not a `_FeatureColumn`
 787       instance.
 788   """
 789   result = {}
 790   for column in feature_columns:
 791     if not isinstance(column, _FeatureColumn):
 792       raise ValueError(
 793           'All feature_columns must be _FeatureColumn instances. '
 794           'Given: {}'.format(column))
 795     config = column._parse_example_spec  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 796     for key, value in six.iteritems(config):
 797       if key in result and value != result[key]:
 798         raise ValueError(
 799             'feature_columns contain different parse_spec for key '
 800             '{}. Given {} and {}'.format(key, value, result[key]))
 801     result.update(config)
 802   return result

 805 @tf_export('feature_column.embedding_column')
 806 def embedding_column(
 807     categorical_column, dimension, combiner='mean', initializer=None,
 808     ckpt_to_load_from=None, tensor_name_in_ckpt=None, max_norm=None,
 809     trainable=True):
 810   """`_DenseColumn` that converts from sparse, categorical input.
 811 
 812   Use this when your inputs are sparse, but you want to convert them to a dense
 813   representation (e.g., to feed to a DNN).
 814 
 815   Inputs must be a `_CategoricalColumn` created by any of the
 816   `categorical_column_*` function. Here is an example of using
 817   `embedding_column` with `DNNClassifier`:
 818 
 819   ```python
 820   video_id = categorical_column_with_identity(
 821       key='video_id', num_buckets=1000000, default_value=0)
 822   columns = [embedding_column(video_id, 9),...]
 823 
 824   estimator = tf.estimator.DNNClassifier(feature_columns=columns, ...)
 825 
 826   label_column = ...
 827   def input_fn():
 828     features = tf.parse_example(
 829         ..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns + [label_column]))
 830     labels = features.pop(label_column.name)
 831     return features, labels
 832 
 833   estimator.train(input_fn=input_fn, steps=100)
 834   ```
 835 
 836   Here is an example using `embedding_column` with model_fn:
 837 
 838   ```python
 839   def model_fn(features, ...):
 840     video_id = categorical_column_with_identity(
 841         key='video_id', num_buckets=1000000, default_value=0)
 842     columns = [embedding_column(video_id, 9),...]
 843     dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
 844     # Form DNN layers, calculate loss, and return EstimatorSpec.
 845     ...
 846   ```
 847 
 848   Args:
 849     categorical_column: A `_CategoricalColumn` created by a
 850       `categorical_column_with_*` function. This column produces the sparse IDs
 851       that are inputs to the embedding lookup.
 852     dimension: An integer specifying dimension of the embedding, must be > 0.
 853     combiner: A string specifying how to reduce if there are multiple entries
 854       in a single row. Currently 'mean', 'sqrtn' and 'sum' are supported, with
 855       'mean' the default. 'sqrtn' often achieves good accuracy, in particular
 856       with bag-of-words columns. Each of this can be thought as example level
 857       normalizations on the column. For more information, see
 858       `tf.embedding_lookup_sparse`.
 859     initializer: A variable initializer function to be used in embedding
 860       variable initialization. If not specified, defaults to
 861       `tf.truncated_normal_initializer` with mean `0.0` and standard deviation
 862       `1/sqrt(dimension)`.
 863     ckpt_to_load_from: String representing checkpoint name/pattern from which to
 864       restore column weights. Required if `tensor_name_in_ckpt` is not `None`.
 865     tensor_name_in_ckpt: Name of the `Tensor` in `ckpt_to_load_from` from
 866       which to restore the column weights. Required if `ckpt_to_load_from` is
 867       not `None`.
 868     max_norm: If not `None`, embedding values are l2-normalized to this value.
 869     trainable: Whether or not the embedding is trainable. Default is True.
 870 
 871   Returns:
 872     `_DenseColumn` that converts from sparse input.
 873 
 874   Raises:
 875     ValueError: if `dimension` not > 0.
 876     ValueError: if exactly one of `ckpt_to_load_from` and `tensor_name_in_ckpt`
 877       is specified.
 878     ValueError: if `initializer` is specified and is not callable.
 879     RuntimeError: If eager execution is enabled.
 880   """
 881   if (dimension is None) or (dimension < 1):
 882     raise ValueError('Invalid dimension {}.'.format(dimension))
 883   if (ckpt_to_load_from is None) != (tensor_name_in_ckpt is None):
 884     raise ValueError('Must specify both `ckpt_to_load_from` and '
 885                      '`tensor_name_in_ckpt` or none of them.')
 886 
 887   if (initializer is not None) and (not callable(initializer)):
 888     raise ValueError('initializer must be callable if specified. '
 889                      'Embedding of column_name: {}'.format(
 890                          categorical_column.name))
 891   if initializer is None:
 892     initializer = init_ops.truncated_normal_initializer(
 893         mean=0.0, stddev=1 / math.sqrt(dimension))
 894 
 895   embedding_shape = categorical_column._num_buckets, dimension  # pylint: disable=protected-access
 896 
 897   def _creator(weight_collections, scope):
 898     embedding_column_layer = _EmbeddingColumnLayer(
 899         embedding_shape=embedding_shape,
 900         initializer=initializer,
 901         weight_collections=weight_collections,
 902         trainable=trainable,
 903         name='embedding_column_layer')
 904     return embedding_column_layer(None, scope=scope)  # pylint: disable=not-callable
 905 
 906   return _EmbeddingColumn(
 907       categorical_column=categorical_column,
 908       dimension=dimension,
 909       combiner=combiner,
 910       layer_creator=_creator,
 911       ckpt_to_load_from=ckpt_to_load_from,
 912       tensor_name_in_ckpt=tensor_name_in_ckpt,
 913       max_norm=max_norm,
 914       trainable=trainable)
 915

 917 @tf_export('feature_column.shared_embedding_columns')
 918 def shared_embedding_columns(
 919     categorical_columns, dimension, combiner='mean', initializer=None,
 920     shared_embedding_collection_name=None, ckpt_to_load_from=None,
 921     tensor_name_in_ckpt=None, max_norm=None, trainable=True):
 922   """List of dense columns that convert from sparse, categorical input.
 923 
 924   This is similar to `embedding_column`, except that it produces a list of
 925   embedding columns that share the same embedding weights.
 926 
 927   Use this when your inputs are sparse and of the same type (e.g. watched and
 928   impression video IDs that share the same vocabulary), and you want to convert
 929   them to a dense representation (e.g., to feed to a DNN).
 930 
 931   Inputs must be a list of categorical columns created by any of the
 932   `categorical_column_*` function. They must all be of the same type and have
 933   the same arguments except `key`. E.g. they can be
 934   categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file with the same vocabulary_file. Some or
 935   all columns could also be weighted_categorical_column.
 936 
 937   Here is an example embedding of two features for a DNNClassifier model:
 938 
 939   ```python
 940   watched_video_id = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
 941       'watched_video_id', video_vocabulary_file, video_vocabulary_size)
 942   impression_video_id = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
 943       'impression_video_id', video_vocabulary_file, video_vocabulary_size)
 944   columns = shared_embedding_columns(
 945       [watched_video_id, impression_video_id], dimension=10)
 946 
 947   estimator = tf.estimator.DNNClassifier(feature_columns=columns, ...)
 948 
 949   label_column = ...
 950   def input_fn():
 951     features = tf.parse_example(
 952         ..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns + [label_column]))
 953     labels = features.pop(label_column.name)
 954     return features, labels
 955 
 956   estimator.train(input_fn=input_fn, steps=100)
 957   ```
 958 
 959   Here is an example using `shared_embedding_columns` with model_fn:
 960 
 961   ```python
 962   def model_fn(features, ...):
 963     watched_video_id = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
 964         'watched_video_id', video_vocabulary_file, video_vocabulary_size)
 965     impression_video_id = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
 966         'impression_video_id', video_vocabulary_file, video_vocabulary_size)
 967     columns = shared_embedding_columns(
 968         [watched_video_id, impression_video_id], dimension=10)
 969     dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
 970     # Form DNN layers, calculate loss, and return EstimatorSpec.
 971     ...
 972   ```
 973 
 974   Args:
 975     categorical_columns: List of categorical columns created by a
 976       `categorical_column_with_*` function. These columns produce the sparse IDs
 977       that are inputs to the embedding lookup. All columns must be of the same
 978       type and have the same arguments except `key`. E.g. they can be
 979       categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file with the same vocabulary_file.
 980       Some or all columns could also be weighted_categorical_column.
 981     dimension: An integer specifying dimension of the embedding, must be > 0.
 982     combiner: A string specifying how to reduce if there are multiple entries
 983       in a single row. Currently 'mean', 'sqrtn' and 'sum' are supported, with
 984       'mean' the default. 'sqrtn' often achieves good accuracy, in particular
 985       with bag-of-words columns. Each of this can be thought as example level
 986       normalizations on the column. For more information, see
 987       `tf.embedding_lookup_sparse`.
 988     initializer: A variable initializer function to be used in embedding
 989       variable initialization. If not specified, defaults to
 990       `tf.truncated_normal_initializer` with mean `0.0` and standard deviation
 991       `1/sqrt(dimension)`.
 992     shared_embedding_collection_name: Optional name of the collection where
 993       shared embedding weights are added. If not given, a reasonable name will
 994       be chosen based on the names of `categorical_columns`. This is also used
 995       in `variable_scope` when creating shared embedding weights.
 996     ckpt_to_load_from: String representing checkpoint name/pattern from which to
 997       restore column weights. Required if `tensor_name_in_ckpt` is not `None`.
 998     tensor_name_in_ckpt: Name of the `Tensor` in `ckpt_to_load_from` from
 999       which to restore the column weights. Required if `ckpt_to_load_from` is
1000       not `None`.
1001     max_norm: If not `None`, each embedding is clipped if its l2-norm is
1002       larger than this value, before combining.
1003     trainable: Whether or not the embedding is trainable. Default is True.
1004 
1005   Returns:
1006     A list of dense columns that converts from sparse input. The order of
1007     results follows the ordering of `categorical_columns`.
1008 
1009   Raises:
1010     ValueError: if `dimension` not > 0.
1011     ValueError: if any of the given `categorical_columns` is of different type
1012       or has different arguments than the others.
1013     ValueError: if exactly one of `ckpt_to_load_from` and `tensor_name_in_ckpt`
1014       is specified.
1015     ValueError: if `initializer` is specified and is not callable.
1016     RuntimeError: if eager execution is enabled.
1017   """
1018   if context.executing_eagerly():
1019     raise RuntimeError('shared_embedding_columns are not supported when eager '
1020                        'execution is enabled.')
1021 
1022   if (dimension is None) or (dimension < 1):
1023     raise ValueError('Invalid dimension {}.'.format(dimension))
1024   if (ckpt_to_load_from is None) != (tensor_name_in_ckpt is None):
1025     raise ValueError('Must specify both `ckpt_to_load_from` and '
1026                      '`tensor_name_in_ckpt` or none of them.')
1027 
1028   if (initializer is not None) and (not callable(initializer)):
1029     raise ValueError('initializer must be callable if specified.')
1030   if initializer is None:
1031     initializer = init_ops.truncated_normal_initializer(
1032         mean=0.0, stddev=1. / math.sqrt(dimension))
1033 
1034   # Sort the columns so the default collection name is deterministic even if the
1035   # user passes columns from an unsorted collection, such as dict.values().
1036   sorted_columns = sorted(categorical_columns, key=lambda x: x.name)
1037 
1038   c0 = sorted_columns[0]
1039   num_buckets = c0._num_buckets  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1040   if not isinstance(c0, _CategoricalColumn):
1041     raise ValueError(
1042         'All categorical_columns must be subclasses of _CategoricalColumn. '
1043         'Given: {}, of type: {}'.format(c0, type(c0)))
1044   if isinstance(c0, _WeightedCategoricalColumn):
1045     c0 = c0.categorical_column
1046   for c in sorted_columns[1:]:
1047     if isinstance(c, _WeightedCategoricalColumn):
1048       c = c.categorical_column
1049     if not isinstance(c, type(c0)):
1050       raise ValueError(
1051           'To use shared_embedding_column, all categorical_columns must have '
1052           'the same type, or be weighted_categorical_column of the same type. '
1053           'Given column: {} of type: {} does not match given column: {} of '
1054           'type: {}'.format(c0, type(c0), c, type(c)))
1055     if num_buckets != c._num_buckets:  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1056       raise ValueError(
1057           'To use shared_embedding_column, all categorical_columns must have '
1058           'the same number of buckets. Given column: {} with buckets: {} does  '
1059           'not match column: {} with buckets: {}'.format(
1060               c0, num_buckets, c, c._num_buckets))  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1061 
1062   if not shared_embedding_collection_name:
1063     shared_embedding_collection_name = '_'.join(c.name for c in sorted_columns)
1064     shared_embedding_collection_name += '_shared_embedding'
1065 
1066   result = []
1067   for column in categorical_columns:
1068     result.append(
1069         _SharedEmbeddingColumn(
1070             categorical_column=column,
1071             initializer=initializer,
1072             dimension=dimension,
1073             combiner=combiner,
1074             shared_embedding_collection_name=shared_embedding_collection_name,
1075             ckpt_to_load_from=ckpt_to_load_from,
1076             tensor_name_in_ckpt=tensor_name_in_ckpt,
1077             max_norm=max_norm,
1078             trainable=trainable))
1079 
1080   return result

1083 @tf_export('feature_column.numeric_column')
1084 def numeric_column(key,
1085                    shape=(1,),
1086                    default_value=None,
1087                    dtype=dtypes.float32,
1088                    normalizer_fn=None):
1089   """Represents real valued or numerical features.
1090 
1091   Example:
1092 
1093   ```python
1094   price = numeric_column('price')
1095   columns = [price, ...]
1096   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1097   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1098 
1099   # or
1100   bucketized_price = bucketized_column(price, boundaries=[...])
1101   columns = [bucketized_price, ...]
1102   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1103   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1104   ```
1105 
1106   Args:
1107     key: A unique string identifying the input feature. It is used as the
1108       column name and the dictionary key for feature parsing configs, feature
1109       `Tensor` objects, and feature columns.
1110     shape: An iterable of integers specifies the shape of the `Tensor`. An
1111       integer can be given which means a single dimension `Tensor` with given
1112       width. The `Tensor` representing the column will have the shape of
1113       [batch_size] + `shape`.
1114     default_value: A single value compatible with `dtype` or an iterable of
1115       values compatible with `dtype` which the column takes on during
1116       `tf.Example` parsing if data is missing. A default value of `None` will
1117       cause `tf.parse_example` to fail if an example does not contain this
1118       column. If a single value is provided, the same value will be applied as
1119       the default value for every item. If an iterable of values is provided,
1120       the shape of the `default_value` should be equal to the given `shape`.
1121     dtype: defines the type of values. Default value is `tf.float32`. Must be a
1122       non-quantized, real integer or floating point type.
1123     normalizer_fn: If not `None`, a function that can be used to normalize the
1124       value of the tensor after `default_value` is applied for parsing.
1125       Normalizer function takes the input `Tensor` as its argument, and returns
1126       the output `Tensor`. (e.g. lambda x: (x - 3.0) / 4.2). Please note that
1127       even though the most common use case of this function is normalization, it
1128       can be used for any kind of Tensorflow transformations.
1129 
1130   Returns:
1131     A `_NumericColumn`.
1132 
1133   Raises:
1134     TypeError: if any dimension in shape is not an int
1135     ValueError: if any dimension in shape is not a positive integer
1136     TypeError: if `default_value` is an iterable but not compatible with `shape`
1137     TypeError: if `default_value` is not compatible with `dtype`.
1138     ValueError: if `dtype` is not convertible to `tf.float32`.
1139   """
1140   shape = _check_shape(shape, key)
1141   if not (dtype.is_integer or dtype.is_floating):
1142     raise ValueError('dtype must be convertible to float. '
1143                      'dtype: {}, key: {}'.format(dtype, key))
1144   default_value = _check_default_value(shape, default_value, dtype, key)
1145 
1146   if normalizer_fn is not None and not callable(normalizer_fn):
1147     raise TypeError(
1148         'normalizer_fn must be a callable. Given: {}'.format(normalizer_fn))
1149 
1150   _assert_key_is_string(key)
1151   return _NumericColumn(
1152       key,
1153       shape=shape,
1154       default_value=default_value,
1155       dtype=dtype,
1156       normalizer_fn=normalizer_fn)

1159 @tf_export('feature_column.bucketized_column')
1160 def bucketized_column(source_column, boundaries):
1161   """Represents discretized dense input.
1162 
1163   Buckets include the left boundary, and exclude the right boundary. Namely,
1164   `boundaries=[0., 1., 2.]` generates buckets `(-inf, 0.)`, `[0., 1.)`,
1165   `[1., 2.)`, and `[2., +inf)`.
1166 
1167   For example, if the inputs are
1168 
1169   ```python
1170   boundaries = [0, 10, 100]
1171   input tensor = [[-5, 10000]
1172                   [150,   10]
1173                   [5,    100]]
1174   ```
1175 
1176   then the output will be
1177 
1178   ```python
1179   output = [[0, 3]
1180             [3, 2]
1181             [1, 3]]
1182   ```
1183 
1184   Example:
1185 
1186   ```python
1187   price = numeric_column('price')
1188   bucketized_price = bucketized_column(price, boundaries=[...])
1189   columns = [bucketized_price, ...]
1190   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1191   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1192 
1193   # or
1194   columns = [bucketized_price, ...]
1195   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1196   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1197   ```
1198 
1199   `bucketized_column` can also be crossed with another categorical column using
1200   `crossed_column`:
1201 
1202   ```python
1203   price = numeric_column('price')
1204   # bucketized_column converts numerical feature to a categorical one.
1205   bucketized_price = bucketized_column(price, boundaries=[...])
1206   # 'keywords' is a string feature.
1207   price_x_keywords = crossed_column([bucketized_price, 'keywords'], 50K)
1208   columns = [price_x_keywords, ...]
1209   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1210   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1211   ```
1212 
1213   Args:
1214     source_column: A one-dimensional dense column which is generated with
1215       `numeric_column`.
1216     boundaries: A sorted list or tuple of floats specifying the boundaries.
1217 
1218   Returns:
1219     A `_BucketizedColumn`.
1220 
1221   Raises:
1222     ValueError: If `source_column` is not a numeric column, or if it is not
1223       one-dimensional.
1224     ValueError: If `boundaries` is not a sorted list or tuple.
1225   """
1226   if not isinstance(source_column, _NumericColumn):
1227     raise ValueError(
1228         'source_column must be a column generated with numeric_column(). '
1229         'Given: {}'.format(source_column))
1230   if len(source_column.shape) > 1:
1231     raise ValueError(
1232         'source_column must be one-dimensional column. '
1233         'Given: {}'.format(source_column))
1234   if (not boundaries or
1235       not (isinstance(boundaries, list) or isinstance(boundaries, tuple))):
1236     raise ValueError('boundaries must be a sorted list.')
1237   for i in range(len(boundaries) - 1):
1238     if boundaries[i] >= boundaries[i + 1]:
1239       raise ValueError('boundaries must be a sorted list.')
1240   return _BucketizedColumn(source_column, tuple(boundaries))
1241

1243 def _assert_string_or_int(dtype, prefix):
1244   if (dtype != dtypes.string) and (not dtype.is_integer):
1245     raise ValueError(
1246         '{} dtype must be string or integer. dtype: {}.'.format(prefix, dtype))
1247 
1248 
1249 def _assert_key_is_string(key):
1250   if not isinstance(key, six.string_types):
1251     raise ValueError(
1252         'key must be a string. Got: type {}. Given key: {}.'.format(
1253             type(key), key))

1260   """Represents sparse feature where ids are set by hashing.
1261

1284   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1285   ```
1286 
1287   Args:
1288     key: A unique string identifying the input feature. It is used as the
1289       column name and the dictionary key for feature parsing configs, feature
1290       `Tensor` objects, and feature columns.
1291     hash_bucket_size: An int > 1. The number of buckets.
1292     dtype: The type of features. Only string and integer types are supported.
1293 
1294   Returns:
1295     A `_HashedCategoricalColumn`.
1296 
1297   Raises:
1298     ValueError: `hash_bucket_size` is not greater than 1.
1299     ValueError: `dtype` is neither string nor integer.
1300   """
1301   if hash_bucket_size is None:
1302     raise ValueError('hash_bucket_size must be set. ' 'key: {}'.format(key))
1303 
1304   if hash_bucket_size < 1:
1305     raise ValueError('hash_bucket_size must be at least 1. '
1306                      'hash_bucket_size: {}, key: {}'.format(
1307                          hash_bucket_size, key))
1308 
1309   _assert_key_is_string(key)
1310   _assert_string_or_int(dtype, prefix='column_name: {}'.format(key))
1311 
1312   return _HashedCategoricalColumn(key, hash_bucket_size, dtype)

1315 @tf_export('feature_column.categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file')
1316 def categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(key,
1317                                             vocabulary_file,
1318                                             vocabulary_size=None,
1319                                             num_oov_buckets=0,
1320                                             default_value=None,
1321                                             dtype=dtypes.string):
1322   """A `_CategoricalColumn` with a vocabulary file.
1323 
1324   Use this when your inputs are in string or integer format, and you have a
1325   vocabulary file that maps each value to an integer ID. By default,
1326   out-of-vocabulary values are ignored. Use either (but not both) of
1327   `num_oov_buckets` and `default_value` to specify how to include
1328   out-of-vocabulary values.
1329 
1330   For input dictionary `features`, `features[key]` is either `Tensor` or
1331   `SparseTensor`. If `Tensor`, missing values can be represented by `-1` for int
1332   and `''` for string, which will be dropped by this feature column.
1333 
1334   Example with `num_oov_buckets`:
1335   File '/us/states.txt' contains 50 lines, each with a 2-character U.S. state
1336   abbreviation. All inputs with values in that file are assigned an ID 0-49,
1337   corresponding to its line number. All other values are hashed and assigned an
1338   ID 50-54.
1339 
1340   ```python
1341   states = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
1342       key='states', vocabulary_file='/us/states.txt', vocabulary_size=50,
1343       num_oov_buckets=5)
1344   columns = [states, ...]
1345   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1346   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1347   ```
1348 
1349   Example with `default_value`:
1350   File '/us/states.txt' contains 51 lines - the first line is 'XX', and the
1351   other 50 each have a 2-character U.S. state abbreviation. Both a literal 'XX'
1352   in input, and other values missing from the file, will be assigned ID 0. All
1353   others are assigned the corresponding line number 1-50.
1354 
1355   ```python
1356   states = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
1357       key='states', vocabulary_file='/us/states.txt', vocabulary_size=51,
1358       default_value=0)
1359   columns = [states, ...]
1360   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1361   linear_prediction, _, _ = linear_model(features, columns)
1362   ```
1363 
1364   And to make an embedding with either:
1365 
1366   ```python
1367   columns = [embedding_column(states, 3),...]
1368   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1369   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1370   ```
1371 
1372   Args:
1373     key: A unique string identifying the input feature. It is used as the
1374       column name and the dictionary key for feature parsing configs, feature
1375       `Tensor` objects, and feature columns.
1376     vocabulary_file: The vocabulary file name.
1377     vocabulary_size: Number of the elements in the vocabulary. This must be no
1378       greater than length of `vocabulary_file`, if less than length, later
1379       values are ignored. If None, it is set to the length of `vocabulary_file`.
1380     num_oov_buckets: Non-negative integer, the number of out-of-vocabulary
1381       buckets. All out-of-vocabulary inputs will be assigned IDs in the range
1382       `[vocabulary_size, vocabulary_size+num_oov_buckets)` based on a hash of
1383       the input value. A positive `num_oov_buckets` can not be specified with
1384       `default_value`.
1385     default_value: The integer ID value to return for out-of-vocabulary feature
1386       values, defaults to `-1`. This can not be specified with a positive
1387       `num_oov_buckets`.
1388     dtype: The type of features. Only string and integer types are supported.
1389 
1390   Returns:
1391     A `_CategoricalColumn` with a vocabulary file.
1392 
1393   Raises:
1394     ValueError: `vocabulary_file` is missing or cannot be opened.
1395     ValueError: `vocabulary_size` is missing or < 1.
1396     ValueError: `num_oov_buckets` is a negative integer.
1397     ValueError: `num_oov_buckets` and `default_value` are both specified.
1398     ValueError: `dtype` is neither string nor integer.
1399   """
1400   if not vocabulary_file:
1401     raise ValueError('Missing vocabulary_file in {}.'.format(key))
1402 
1403   if vocabulary_size is None:
1404     if not gfile.Exists(vocabulary_file):
1405       raise ValueError('vocabulary_file in {} does not exist.'.format(key))
1406 
1407     with gfile.GFile(vocabulary_file) as f:
1408       vocabulary_size = sum(1 for _ in f)
1409     logging.info(
1410         'vocabulary_size = %d in %s is inferred from the number of elements '
1411         'in the vocabulary_file %s.', vocabulary_size, key, vocabulary_file)
1412 
1413   # `vocabulary_size` isn't required for lookup, but it is for `_num_buckets`.
1414   if vocabulary_size < 1:
1415     raise ValueError('Invalid vocabulary_size in {}.'.format(key))
1416   if num_oov_buckets:
1417     if default_value is not None:
1418       raise ValueError(
1419           'Can\'t specify both num_oov_buckets and default_value in {}.'.format(
1420               key))
1421     if num_oov_buckets < 0:
1422       raise ValueError('Invalid num_oov_buckets {} in {}.'.format(
1423           num_oov_buckets, key))
1424   _assert_string_or_int(dtype, prefix='column_name: {}'.format(key))
1425   _assert_key_is_string(key)
1426   return _VocabularyFileCategoricalColumn(
1427       key=key,
1428       vocabulary_file=vocabulary_file,
1429       vocabulary_size=vocabulary_size,
1430       num_oov_buckets=0 if num_oov_buckets is None else num_oov_buckets,
1431       default_value=-1 if default_value is None else default_value,
1432       dtype=dtype)

1435 @tf_export('feature_column.categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list')
1436 def categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list(

1449

1451   In the following example, each input in `vocabulary_list` is assigned an ID

1453   inputs are hashed and assigned an ID 4-5.

1458       num_oov_buckets=2)

1461   linear_prediction, _, _ = linear_model(features, columns)
1462   ```
1463 
1464   Example with `default_value`:
1465   In the following example, each input in `vocabulary_list` is assigned an ID
1466   0-4 corresponding to its index (e.g., input 'B' produces output 3). All other
1467   inputs are assigned `default_value` 0.
1468 
1469 
1470   ```python
1471   colors = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list(
1472       key='colors', vocabulary_list=('X', 'R', 'G', 'B', 'Y'), default_value=0)
1473   columns = [colors, ...]
1474   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1475   linear_prediction, _, _ = linear_model(features, columns)
1476   ```
1477 
1478   And to make an embedding with either:
1479 
1480   ```python
1481   columns = [embedding_column(colors, 3),...]
1482   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1483   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1484   ```
1485 
1486   Args:
1487     key: A unique string identifying the input feature. It is used as the
1488       column name and the dictionary key for feature parsing configs, feature
1489       `Tensor` objects, and feature columns.
1490     vocabulary_list: An ordered iterable defining the vocabulary. Each feature
1491       is mapped to the index of its value (if present) in `vocabulary_list`.
1492       Must be castable to `dtype`.
1493     dtype: The type of features. Only string and integer types are supported.
1494       If `None`, it will be inferred from `vocabulary_list`.
1495     default_value: The integer ID value to return for out-of-vocabulary feature
1496       values, defaults to `-1`. This can not be specified with a positive
1497       `num_oov_buckets`.

1499       buckets. All out-of-vocabulary inputs will be assigned IDs in the range

1501       hash of the input value. A positive `num_oov_buckets` can not be specified
1502       with `default_value`.
1503

1505     A `_CategoricalColumn` with in-memory vocabulary.

1511     ValueError: if `dtype` is not integer or string.
1512   """
1513   if (vocabulary_list is None) or (len(vocabulary_list) < 1):
1514     raise ValueError(
1515         'vocabulary_list {} must be non-empty, column_name: {}'.format(
1516             vocabulary_list, key))
1517   if len(set(vocabulary_list)) != len(vocabulary_list):
1518     raise ValueError(
1519         'Duplicate keys in vocabulary_list {}, column_name: {}'.format(

1522   if num_oov_buckets:
1523     if default_value != -1:
1524       raise ValueError(
1525           'Can\'t specify both num_oov_buckets and default_value in {}.'.format(
1526               key))
1527     if num_oov_buckets < 0:
1528       raise ValueError('Invalid num_oov_buckets {} in {}.'.format(
1529           num_oov_buckets, key))
1530   _assert_string_or_int(
1531       vocabulary_dtype, prefix='column_name: {} vocabulary'.format(key))
1532   if dtype is None:
1533     dtype = vocabulary_dtype
1534   elif dtype.is_integer != vocabulary_dtype.is_integer:
1535     raise ValueError(
1536         'dtype {} and vocabulary dtype {} do not match, column_name: {}'.format(
1537             dtype, vocabulary_dtype, key))
1538   _assert_string_or_int(dtype, prefix='column_name: {}'.format(key))
1539   _assert_key_is_string(key)
1540 
1541   return _VocabularyListCategoricalColumn(

1546 @tf_export('feature_column.categorical_column_with_identity')
1547 def categorical_column_with_identity(key, num_buckets, default_value=None):
1548   """A `_CategoricalColumn` that returns identity values.
1549 
1550   Use this when your inputs are integers in the range `[0, num_buckets)`, and
1551   you want to use the input value itself as the categorical ID. Values outside
1552   this range will result in `default_value` if specified, otherwise it will
1553   fail.
1554

1556   it doesn't have to be. This might be inefficient, however, if many of IDs
1557   are unused. Consider `categorical_column_with_hash_bucket` in that case.
1558

1560   `SparseTensor`. If `Tensor`, missing values can be represented by `-1` for int
1561   and `''` for string, which will be dropped by this feature column.
1562 
1563   In the following examples, each input in the range `[0, 1000000)` is assigned
1564   the same value. All other inputs are assigned `default_value` 0. Note that a
1565   literal 0 in inputs will result in the same default ID.
1566 
1567   Linear model:
1568 
1569   ```python
1570   video_id = categorical_column_with_identity(
1571       key='video_id', num_buckets=1000000, default_value=0)
1572   columns = [video_id, ...]
1573   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1574   linear_prediction, _, _ = linear_model(features, columns)
1575   ```
1576 
1577   Embedding for a DNN model:
1578 
1579   ```python
1580   columns = [embedding_column(video_id, 9),...]
1581   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1582   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1583   ```
1584 
1585   Args:
1586     key: A unique string identifying the input feature. It is used as the
1587       column name and the dictionary key for feature parsing configs, feature
1588       `Tensor` objects, and feature columns.
1589     num_buckets: Range of inputs and outputs is `[0, num_buckets)`.
1590     default_value: If `None`, this column's graph operations will fail for
1591       out-of-range inputs. Otherwise, this value must be in the range
1592       `[0, num_buckets)`, and will replace inputs in that range.
1593 
1594   Returns:
1595     A `_CategoricalColumn` that returns identity values.
1596 
1597   Raises:
1598     ValueError: if `num_buckets` is less than one.
1599     ValueError: if `default_value` is not in range `[0, num_buckets)`.
1600   """
1601   if num_buckets < 1:
1602     raise ValueError(
1603         'num_buckets {} < 1, column_name {}'.format(num_buckets, key))
1604   if (default_value is not None) and (
1605       (default_value < 0) or (default_value >= num_buckets)):
1606     raise ValueError(
1607         'default_value {} not in range [0, {}), column_name {}'.format(
1608             default_value, num_buckets, key))
1609   _assert_key_is_string(key)
1610   return _IdentityCategoricalColumn(
1611       key=key, num_buckets=num_buckets, default_value=default_value)
1612

1614 @tf_export('feature_column.indicator_column')
1615 def indicator_column(categorical_column):
1616   """Represents multi-hot representation of given categorical column.
1617 
1618   - For DNN model, `indicator_column` can be used to wrap any
1619     `categorical_column_*` (e.g., to feed to DNN). Consider to Use
1620     `embedding_column` if the number of buckets/unique(values) are large.
1621 
1622   - For Wide (aka linear) model, `indicator_column` is the internal
1623     representation for categorical column when passing categorical column
1624     directly (as any element in feature_columns) to `linear_model`. See
1625     `linear_model` for details.
1626 
1627   ```python
1628   name = indicator_column(categorical_column_with_vocabulary_list(
1629       'name', ['bob', 'george', 'wanda'])

1631   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1632   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, columns)
1633 
1634   dense_tensor == [[1, 0, 0]]  # If "name" bytes_list is ["bob"]
1635   dense_tensor == [[1, 0, 1]]  # If "name" bytes_list is ["bob", "wanda"]
1636   dense_tensor == [[2, 0, 0]]  # If "name" bytes_list is ["bob", "bob"]
1637   ```
1638 
1639   Args:
1640     categorical_column: A `_CategoricalColumn` which is created by
1641       `categorical_column_with_*` or `crossed_column` functions.
1642 
1643   Returns:
1644     An `_IndicatorColumn`.
1645   """

1649 @tf_export('feature_column.weighted_categorical_column')
1650 def weighted_categorical_column(
1651     categorical_column, weight_feature_key, dtype=dtypes.float32):
1652   """Applies weight values to a `_CategoricalColumn`.
1653 
1654   Use this when each of your sparse inputs has both an ID and a value. For
1655   example, if you're representing text documents as a collection of word
1656   frequencies, you can provide 2 parallel sparse input features ('terms' and
1657   'frequencies' below).
1658 
1659   Example:
1660 
1661   Input `tf.Example` objects:
1662 
1663   ```proto
1664   [
1665     features {
1666       feature {
1667         key: "terms"
1668         value {bytes_list {value: "very" value: "model"}}
1669       }
1670       feature {
1671         key: "frequencies"
1672         value {float_list {value: 0.3 value: 0.1}}
1673       }
1674     },
1675     features {
1676       feature {
1677         key: "terms"
1678         value {bytes_list {value: "when" value: "course" value: "human"}}
1679       }
1680       feature {
1681         key: "frequencies"
1682         value {float_list {value: 0.4 value: 0.1 value: 0.2}}
1683       }
1684     }
1685   ]
1686   ```
1687 
1688   ```python
1689   categorical_column = categorical_column_with_hash_bucket(
1690       column_name='terms', hash_bucket_size=1000)
1691   weighted_column = weighted_categorical_column(
1692       categorical_column=categorical_column, weight_feature_key='frequencies')
1693   columns = [weighted_column, ...]
1694   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1695   linear_prediction, _, _ = linear_model(features, columns)
1696   ```
1697 
1698   This assumes the input dictionary contains a `SparseTensor` for key
1699   'terms', and a `SparseTensor` for key 'frequencies'. These 2 tensors must have
1700   the same indices and dense shape.
1701 
1702   Args:
1703     categorical_column: A `_CategoricalColumn` created by
1704       `categorical_column_with_*` functions.
1705     weight_feature_key: String key for weight values.
1706     dtype: Type of weights, such as `tf.float32`. Only float and integer weights
1707       are supported.
1708 
1709   Returns:
1710     A `_CategoricalColumn` composed of two sparse features: one represents id,
1711     the other represents weight (value) of the id feature in that example.
1712 
1713   Raises:
1714     ValueError: if `dtype` is not convertible to float.
1715   """
1716   if (dtype is None) or not (dtype.is_integer or dtype.is_floating):
1717     raise ValueError('dtype {} is not convertible to float.'.format(dtype))
1718   return _WeightedCategoricalColumn(
1719       categorical_column=categorical_column,
1720       weight_feature_key=weight_feature_key,
1721       dtype=dtype)

1724 @tf_export('feature_column.crossed_column')
1725 def crossed_column(keys, hash_bucket_size, hash_key=None):
1726   """Returns a column for performing crosses of categorical features.
1727 
1728   Crossed features will be hashed according to `hash_bucket_size`. Conceptually,
1729   the transformation can be thought of as:
1730     Hash(cartesian product of features) % `hash_bucket_size`
1731 
1732   For example, if the input features are:
1733 
1734   * SparseTensor referred by first key:
1735 
1736     ```python
1737     shape = [2, 2]
1738     {
1739         [0, 0]: "a"
1740         [1, 0]: "b"
1741         [1, 1]: "c"
1742     }
1743     ```
1744 
1745   * SparseTensor referred by second key:
1746 
1747     ```python
1748     shape = [2, 1]
1749     {
1750         [0, 0]: "d"
1751         [1, 0]: "e"
1752     }
1753     ```
1754 
1755   then crossed feature will look like:
1756 
1757   ```python
1758    shape = [2, 2]
1759   {
1760       [0, 0]: Hash64("d", Hash64("a")) % hash_bucket_size
1761       [1, 0]: Hash64("e", Hash64("b")) % hash_bucket_size
1762       [1, 1]: Hash64("e", Hash64("c")) % hash_bucket_size
1763   }
1764   ```
1765 
1766   Here is an example to create a linear model with crosses of string features:
1767 
1768   ```python
1769   keywords_x_doc_terms = crossed_column(['keywords', 'doc_terms'], 50K)
1770   columns = [keywords_x_doc_terms, ...]
1771   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1772   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1773   ```
1774 
1775   You could also use vocabulary lookup before crossing:
1776 
1777   ```python
1778   keywords = categorical_column_with_vocabulary_file(
1779       'keywords', '/path/to/vocabulary/file', vocabulary_size=1K)
1780   keywords_x_doc_terms = crossed_column([keywords, 'doc_terms'], 50K)
1781   columns = [keywords_x_doc_terms, ...]
1782   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1783   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1784   ```
1785 
1786   If an input feature is of numeric type, you can use
1787   `categorical_column_with_identity`, or `bucketized_column`, as in the example:
1788 
1789   ```python
1790   # vertical_id is an integer categorical feature.
1791   vertical_id = categorical_column_with_identity('vertical_id', 10K)
1792   price = numeric_column('price')
1793   # bucketized_column converts numerical feature to a categorical one.
1794   bucketized_price = bucketized_column(price, boundaries=[...])
1795   vertical_id_x_price = crossed_column([vertical_id, bucketized_price], 50K)
1796   columns = [vertical_id_x_price, ...]
1797   features = tf.parse_example(..., features=make_parse_example_spec(columns))
1798   linear_prediction = linear_model(features, columns)
1799   ```
1800 
1801   To use crossed column in DNN model, you need to add it in an embedding column
1802   as in this example:
1803 
1804   ```python
1805   vertical_id_x_price = crossed_column([vertical_id, bucketized_price], 50K)
1806   vertical_id_x_price_embedded = embedding_column(vertical_id_x_price, 10)
1807   dense_tensor = input_layer(features, [vertical_id_x_price_embedded, ...])
1808   ```
1809 
1810   Args:
1811     keys: An iterable identifying the features to be crossed. Each element can
1812       be either:
1813       * string: Will use the corresponding feature which must be of string type.
1814       * `_CategoricalColumn`: Will use the transformed tensor produced by this
1815         column. Does not support hashed categorical column.
1816     hash_bucket_size: An int > 1. The number of buckets.
1817     hash_key: Specify the hash_key that will be used by the `FingerprintCat64`
1818       function to combine the crosses fingerprints on SparseCrossOp (optional).
1819 
1820   Returns:
1821     A `_CrossedColumn`.
1822 
1823   Raises:
1824     ValueError: If `len(keys) < 2`.
1825     ValueError: If any of the keys is neither a string nor `_CategoricalColumn`.
1826     ValueError: If any of the keys is `_HashedCategoricalColumn`.
1827     ValueError: If `hash_bucket_size < 1`.
1828   """
1829   if not hash_bucket_size or hash_bucket_size < 1:
1830     raise ValueError('hash_bucket_size must be > 1. '
1831                      'hash_bucket_size: {}'.format(hash_bucket_size))
1832   if not keys or len(keys) < 2:
1833     raise ValueError(
1834         'keys must be a list with length > 1. Given: {}'.format(keys))
1835   for key in keys:
1836     if (not isinstance(key, six.string_types) and
1837         not isinstance(key, _CategoricalColumn)):
1838       raise ValueError(
1839           'Unsupported key type. All keys must be either string, or '
1840           'categorical column except _HashedCategoricalColumn. '
1841           'Given: {}'.format(key))
1842     if isinstance(key, _HashedCategoricalColumn):
1843       raise ValueError(
1844           'categorical_column_with_hash_bucket is not supported for crossing. '
1845           'Hashing before crossing will increase probability of collision. '
1846           'Instead, use the feature name as a string. Given: {}'.format(key))
1847   return _CrossedColumn(
1848       keys=tuple(keys), hash_bucket_size=hash_bucket_size,
1849       hash_key=hash_key)
1850

2059 def _create_dense_column_weighted_sum(column,
2060                                       builder,
2061                                       units,
2062                                       weight_collections,
2063                                       trainable,
2064                                       weight_var=None):
2065   """Create a weighted sum of a dense column for linear_model."""
2066   tensor = column._get_dense_tensor(  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2067       builder,
2068       weight_collections=weight_collections,
2069       trainable=trainable)
2070   num_elements = column._variable_shape.num_elements()  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2071   batch_size = array_ops.shape(tensor)[0]
2072   tensor = array_ops.reshape(tensor, shape=(batch_size, num_elements))
2073   if weight_var is not None:
2074     weight = weight_var
2075   else:
2076     weight = variable_scope.get_variable(
2077         name='weights',
2078         shape=[num_elements, units],
2079         initializer=init_ops.zeros_initializer(),
2080         trainable=trainable,
2081         collections=weight_collections)
2082   return math_ops.matmul(tensor, weight, name='weighted_sum')

2096       'IdWeightPair', ['id_tensor', 'weight_tensor'])

2108     """Returns an IdWeightPair.
2109 
2110     `IdWeightPair` is a pair of `SparseTensor`s which represents ids and
2111     weights.
2112 
2113     `IdWeightPair.id_tensor` is typically a `batch_size` x `num_buckets`
2114     `SparseTensor` of `int64`. `IdWeightPair.weight_tensor` is either a
2115     `SparseTensor` of `float` or `None` to indicate all weights should be
2116     taken to be 1. If specified, `weight_tensor` must have exactly the same
2117     shape and indices as `sp_ids`. Expected `SparseTensor` is same as parsing
2118     output of a `VarLenFeature` which is a ragged matrix.
2119

2122         create `IdWeightPair`.
2123       weight_collections: List of graph collections to which variables (if any
2124         will be created) are added.

2126         `GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` (see `tf.get_variable`).
